    <item>
      <title>A Lac of Rupees for a Bit of Advice</title>
      <link>https://stories.muthu.co/posts/fairy-tales-a-lac-of-rupees-for-a-bit-of-advice/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://stories.muthu.co/posts/fairy-tales-a-lac-of-rupees-for-a-bit-of-advice/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure class=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;img-container&#34; style=&#34;--w: 1024; --h: 721;&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img loading=&#34;lazy&#34; alt=&#34;Watercolor illustration of the son, a young man with brown hair and simple brown clothes, sitting beside his blind parents (dad with grey hair, mom with dark hair) in their humble home. The son looks determined. Soft, muted colors. The style should be illustrative and children-friendly&#34; src=&#34;https://stories.muthu.co/posts/images/image_fairy-tales-a-lac-of-rupees-for-a-bit-of-advice0.png&#34; width=&#34;1024&#34; height=&#34;721&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Once upon a time, there was a poor, blind dad and mom who depended on their son to help them get by. Every day, the son would go out and ask people for food. He did this for a long time, but he got really tired of living such a tough life. So, he decided to try his luck in a different place.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>A Lesson for Kings</title>
      <link>https://stories.muthu.co/posts/fairy-tales-a-lesson-for-kings/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://stories.muthu.co/posts/fairy-tales-a-lesson-for-kings/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;figure class=&#34;&#34;&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &lt;div class=&#34;img-container&#34; style=&#34;--w: 1024; --h: 721;&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;img loading=&#34;lazy&#34; alt=&#34;Watercolor illustration of the young Prince Brahma-datta (light brown skin, dark curly hair, wearing simple gold-trimmed robes) as a sixteen-year-old student at Takkasila, diligently studying ancient texts with a wise-looking guru (white hair, long beard, saffron robes). Lush green trees and traditional buildings in the background. Soft, warm color palette.&#34; src=&#34;https://stories.muthu.co/posts/images/image_fairy-tales-a-lesson-for-kings0.png&#34; width=&#34;1024&#34; height=&#34;721&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/figure&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Once upon a time, a long, long time ago, when King Brahma-datta was in charge of Benares, the future Buddha was born as his son! When it was time to give the little prince a name, they called him Prince Brahma-datta. He grew up big and strong, and when he turned sixteen, he went to a special school called Takkasila. There, he learned all sorts of amazing things. After his dad, the king, passed away, he became the new king and promised to be fair and kind to everyone.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
